```lean
lemma lemma2 :
    ∃ f : Set.Icc 1 8 → Fin 2, ¬coloring_is_good f := by
  use coloring_of_eight
  intro h
  obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, hj2⟩, hij1, hij2, hc1, hc2⟩ := h
  dsimp [coloring_of_eight] at *
  interval_cases i <;>
    (try omega) <;>
    (try {
      have hj3 : (j : ℕ) ≤ 8 := by omega
      interval_cases j <;>
        (try omega) <;>
        (try {
          norm_num [Fin.ext_iff, Fin.val_zero, Fin.val_one, Set.mem_Icc] at hc1 hc2 ⊢ <;>
          (try contradiction) <;>
          (try {
            simp_all [Set.Icc, Fin.val_succ, Fin.val_zero]
            <;> norm_num at *
            <;>
            (try omega)
          })
        })
    })
  <;>
  (try {
    simp_all [Set.Icc, Fin.val_succ, Fin.val_zero]
    <;> norm_num at *
    <;>
    (try omega)
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    aesop
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    exfalso
    <;> simp_all [Set.Icc, Fin.val_succ, Fin.val_zero]
    <;> norm_num at *
    <;>
    (try omega)
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    exfalso
    <;> aesop
  })
```

The proof leverages exhaustive case analysis on `i` and `j` using `interval_cases`, and handles the various arithmetic constraints using `omega`. The `norm_num` tactic is used to simplify the hypotheses and derive contradictions when necessary. 

Each branch checks that the assumptions `hc1` and `hc2` are violated, whenever possible. 

The cases are designed carefully to ensure that no valid triple `(i, j, 2*j - i)` exists with the required properties for the specific coloring of the 8 points. The `aesop` and `exfalso` tactics are used as closing methods when contradictions are derived. 

This approach is efficient and exhaustive, given that the number of cases is small. 

